Movies by the Numbers: What makes a movie successful?¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

The TMDB dataset provides data about movies: revenue, genres, directors, budget, popularity, release year, etc. The data is in numerical and text formats.

From the data set notes: "The final two columns ending with “_adj” show the budget and revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time."

I aim to explore the following questions:

  1. Do actors matter?

    What is the average revenue of all the movies in which actors appear? Does sample size matter? What about minimum number of appearances?

  2. Can you buy a high-revenue movie?

    Does a higher budget generally mean that the movie will make more money?

  3. Could popularity predict revenue?

    Can we predict revenue based on what we know about the popularity of a movie?

  4. Genres and Budget Exploration

    * What are the total budgets for each genre? * What is the average budget for a movie in each genre? * Which genre has the most movies in this dataset?

General Properties¶

  • 10866 entries
  • 21 columns
  • 2936 completely non-null rows (limited by the homepage column, which isn't being used in this analysis)
  • The cast column is a string with actor's names separated by '|', which needs to be modified for this project.

The dataset begins with movies released in or after 1960, and 75% of the movies were released in or after 1995.

Cleaning the Data:¶

Shape¶

  • Remove all movies with release dates prior to 1995, leaving 75% of the dataset
  • Remove columns that won't be used for this analysis
  • Remove movies with 0 values in at least one column
  • Remove movies with NaN values (3 from cast column, 1 from director column)

2963 Movies Remain¶

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Research Question 1: Do actors matter?¶

This dataset includes the top 5 actors appearing in each movie in main character roles.

What is the average revenue of all the movies in which actors appear? Does sample size matter? What about minimum number of appearances?

In [13]:
# Explore different sample sizes and minimum number of appearances
# 4/100, 6/250, 10/500, 15/1000 25/len(movie_db)

# Number of movies to include in the metric:
movie_set = len(movie_db)

# Minimum number of appearances allowable:
actor_appearances = 25

# Top Grossing Movies: 
top_grossing = movie_db.sort_values(by='revenue_adj', ascending=False).head(movie_set)
In [14]:
# Create a dataframe with an actors column that contains lists of actors and a revenue column, indexed by movie title

actors_list = pd.DataFrame()
revenues = dict()
data1 = top_grossing[['cast', 'title', 'revenue_adj']].values
for row, title, revenue in data1:
    revenue = revenue / 1000000
    revenues[title] = revenue
    if isinstance(row, str):
        row = row.split(sep='|')
        actors_list[title] = row, revenue
actors_list = actors_list.T
actors_list[1] = actors_list[1].astype(float)

# Create a dataframe with all of the information needed to answer the question:
# Total and average revenue of all movies in which an actor appears
# Number of movies in which each actor appears

appearances = dict()
total_revenue = dict()
for title, actors, revenue in actors_list.itertuples():
    for actor in actors:
        if actor in total_revenue:
            total_revenue[actor] += revenues[title]
        else:
            total_revenue[actor] = revenues[title]
        if actor in appearances:
            appearances[actor] += 1
        else:
            appearances[actor] = 1

appearances_sorted = dict(sorted(appearances.items(), key=lambda x:x[1], reverse=True))
actor_metrics = pd.DataFrame(appearances, index=["Appearances"]).T
actor_metrics['Total Revenue'] = actor_metrics.index.map(total_revenue)
actor_metrics['Average Revenue'] = actor_metrics['Total Revenue']/actor_metrics['Appearances']
actor_metrics = actor_metrics.sort_values(by='Average Revenue', ascending=False)
actor_metrics = actor_metrics[actor_metrics['Appearances'] > actor_appearances]
In [16]:
#plot average revenue per movie in which each actor appears

xs = actor_metrics.index
x_width = len(xs) * 1.4
ys = actor_metrics['Average Revenue']
ls = actor_metrics['Appearances']
plt.figure(figsize=(24, 12))
plt.title("Average Revenue Generated per Movie Appearance by Actor (in millions)", fontsize=18)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.xlabel(f"Actors appearing in at least {actor_appearances} of the top-grossing {movie_set} movies", fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel("Average revenue for all movies in which each actor appeared (in millions)", fontsize=15)
plt.bar(xs, ys, width=.9)
for x, y, l in zip(xs, ys, ls):
    label = f'{l} movies'
    plt.annotate(label, (x, y), textcoords="offset points", xytext=(0, 10), ha='center', fontsize=11)
plt.show()

Research Question 2: Can you buy a good movie?¶

It makes sense that a higher budget leads to greater revenue, let's test that hypothesis

In [17]:
# the data is already configured to answer this question, create a plot that tells a clear and concise story

x = movie_db['budget_adj']
y = movie_db['revenue_adj']
corr = np.corrcoef(x, y)
m, b = np.polyfit(x, y, 1)
plt.figure(figsize=(24, 12))
plt.suptitle("Budget and Revenue in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation", fontsize=18)
info = f'Correlation coefficient between Budget and Revenue: {corr[0][1].round(2)}'
plt.title(info, fontsize=15)
plt.xlabel(f"Budget", fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel("Revenue", fontsize=15)

colors = movie_db['budget_adj']
cmap = cc.cm.kgy_r
plt.scatter(x, y, c=colors, cmap=cmap)
plt.plot(x, m*x+b, color='red', label=corr)
plt.show()

Research Question 3: Does popularity predict revenue?¶

Metrics: Popularity data, Weighted Vote Average, Revenue Adjusted to 2010 dollars and accounting for inflation.

Could popularity and vote scores be used to predict revenue? Aim to provide a recommendation as to whether it's worth the effort to train an AI.

In [19]:
# filter the dataframe with only the columns needed to answer this question

data3 = movie_db.filter(['title', 'popularity', 'vote_count', 'vote_average', 'revenue_adj'])
In [20]:
# create a weighed average of votes for each movie: vote_average * the proportion of votes each movie received.

votes = sum(data3['vote_count'])
data3['vote_weight'] = data3['vote_count'] / votes
data3['vote_wt_avg'] = data3['vote_average'] * data3['vote_weight']
In [21]:

# calculate the total budget spending for each genre, and the average budget for each movie in each genre

genre_cost = dict()
movie_count = dict()
for genres, budget in genres_list[['genres', 'budget']].values:
    for genre in genres:
        if genre in genre_cost.keys():
            genre_cost[genre] += budget
        else:
            genre_cost[genre] = budget
        if genre in movie_count:
            movie_count[genre] += 1
        else:
            movie_count[genre] = 1

genre_cost = pd.DataFrame(genre_cost, index = ['genres']).T
genre_cost.rename(columns={'genres': 'total_spend'}, inplace=True)
genre_cost['movie_count'] = genre_cost.index.map(movie_count)
genre_cost['avg_budget'] = genre_cost['total_spend'] / genre_cost['movie_count']
genre_cost = genre_cost[genre_cost['total_spend'] > 100000000]

Conclusions¶

The questions I set out to answer:

  1. Do actors matter?

    What is the average revenue of all the movies in which actors appear? Does sample size matter? What about minimum number of appearances? >The sample size and choice of minimum number of appearances matters quite a bit in investigating this question. >For example, with a sample size of 100 movies and a minimum of 4 appearances, Orlando Bloom has the highest average revenue per movie in which he appears. >On the other hand, not limiting the sample (using all 2962 movies in the cleaned dataset) results in a more expected result, with Johnny Depp having the highest average revenue over the 30 movies he's appeared in, almost $300 million per movie. >Overall this is a fairly good way to query actor's affect on the earnings of the movies in which they appear. Samuel L. Jackson has appeared in 40 movies, but his average revenue per movie is just under $200 million.

  2. Can you buy a high-revenue movie?

    Does a higher budget generally mean that the movie will make more money? >With a couple of outliers (high budget, low revenue or low budget, high revenue) there is a fairly strong positive correlation between budget and revenue, with a coefficient of .69. >So yes, a higher budget tends to mean that a movie will make more money, but there are many other factors that may play a greater or equally important role.

  3. Could popularity predict revenue?

    Can we predict revenue based on what we know about the popularity of a movie? >There is a relationship between both the popularity (on social media) and the vote count and average (on this movie website) and revenue. >It might be useful to train an AI to try to predict revenue given popularity scores.

  4. Genres and Budget Exploration

    * What are the total budgets for each genre? * What is the average budget for a movie in each genre? * Which genre has the most movies in this dataset?
